	<div id="p22596" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p22596"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=22596#p22596"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=680">Raynboh</a></strong> &raquo; Feb 3rd, '04, 08:55 </p>

			

			<div class="content">There are two situations in which a MOB will not attack a PET (charmed or summoned).
<br />
<br />(1) There is a PLAYER in the MOB's melee range.
<br />
<br />(2) There are more than FOUR THINGS on the MOB's hate list (THINGS includes PLAYERs and PETs).
<br />
<br />When I play my Cleric, I often charm duo with a Druid in Storms.  We charm a frog pet, and it can tank with no problem, with me healing it during the battle.  I can even send in my hammer pet.  (This means there are 3-4 things on the mob's hate list, depending on whether I have cast my hammer or not).
<br />
<br />Sometimes, we have an Enchanter.  In that case, the Enchanter and Druid *both* have a pet attacking the mob.  In this situation, I can not use my hammer pet, and I can not heal during the battle.  If I do heal during the battle, there will be 5 things on the mob's hate list, and a pet can no longer tank.  At this point, whichever of the 3 players has the most agro will be summoned.
<br />
<br />There.</div>

			

		</div>

		
			<dl class="postprofile" id="profile22596">
