	<div id="p28467" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p28467"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=28467#p28467"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=416">Omniscient</a></strong> &raquo; Mar 4th, '04, 16:18 </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote class="uncited"><div>Chanter + Chanter DC + Druid + Druid DC + Cleric = mass chaos  </div></blockquote>
<br />
<br />
<br />Actually rethinking the situation, I believe there IS a way around it.  I believe I had asked the Druid to hold off sending in her DC pet until my DC pet had killed off around 15% of mobs health.  At that point the only ones on the aggro list were:
<br />
<br />Chanter + Chanter DC + Cleric.
<br />
<br />Then once she engaged her pet it quickly became 2nd on the list of aggro, so at this point it stood at this:
<br />
<br />Chanter + Chanter DC + Druid DC + Cleric.
<br />
<br />Then she would lay in her DoT's in which the initial DC pet would not lose aggro, he would retain it.  So we were still at the 5 on aggro, but because my DC pet had built such a large amount of aggro initially, It never broke off.  Now if I sat, then it would come after me.  
<br />
<br />So, this leaves me wondering if the rule of 5 only decreases the amount of aggro on the pet, and not deletes it entirely.
<br />
<br />Omni</div>

			

		</div>

		
